Purpose: Fix ARCH-1 (HIGH): Correct the incorrect "under 6 MB" claim about DICOM files. Single chest X-rays are 10-50 MB; the Lambda downloads from S3 into memory/tmp, not constrained by the 6 MB invocation payload limit.

[49m[38;5;9m- 99    [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The glue between S3 (image arrives), preprocessing (DICOM parsing, pixel extraction), and SageMaker (inference). Lambda handles the event-driven triggering and result routing. For images under 6 MB (most single DICOM instances), Lambda's memory and timeout are sufficient. For larger studies (multi-slice CT), you'd use Step Functions or batch processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for orchestration.** The glue between S3 (image arrives), preprocessing (DICOM parsing, pixel extraction), and SageMaker (inference). Lambda is triggered by the S3 event notification (a small JSON payload), then downloads the DICOM file from S3 into memory or `/tmp` storage. Single-frame radiographs (10-50 MB) fit comfortably within Lambda's 10 GB memory limit. Configure ephemeral storage to at least 1 GB. For multi-frame DICOM objects (ultrasound cine, digital breast tomosynthesis) or full CT studies processed as a single unit, consider ECS/Fargate tasks or SageMaker Processing jobs instead of Lambda.
